title: Microfoundation Inference for Strategic Prediction

sections.text:
#### Abstract

Often in prediction tasks, the predictive model itself can influence the distribution of the target variable, a phenomenon termed performative prediction. Generally, this influence stems from strategic actions taken by stakeholders with a vested interest in predictive models. A key challenge that hinders the widespread adaptation of performative prediction in machine learning is that practitioners are generally unaware of the social impacts of their predictions. To address this gap, we propose a methodology for learning the distribution map that encapsulates the long-term impacts of predictive models on the population. Specifically, we model agents' responses as a cost-adjusted utility maximization problem and propose estimates for said cost. Our approach leverages optimal transport to align pre-model exposure (ex ante) and post-model exposure (ex post) distributions. We provide a rate of convergence for this proposed estimate and assess its quality through empirical demonstrations on a credit scoring dataset.

## 1 Introduction

Consider a supervised learning scenario where the predictive model triggers actions that alter the target distribution, thereby impacting its own performance. This scenario is referred to as performative prediction (Perdomo et al., 2020) and is prevalent in social prediction contexts, where predictions influence (strategic) individuals. For example, traffic forecasts affect traffic patterns, crime location predictions influence police deployment that may deter crime, and stock price predictions drive trading activity, consequently affecting prices. Campbell's law (Campbell, 1979), which states that

The more any quantitative social indicator is used for social decision-making, the more subject it will be to corruption pressures and the more apt it will be to distort and corrupt the social processes it is intended to monitor.
acknowledges the ubiquity of performativity in social prediction problems.

The learner may respond to this performative distribution shift by frequently retraining the model with new data, but this approach is often impractical, as Perdomo et al. (2020) describes this as a "cat and mouse game of chasing a moving target." They suggest a more structured approach, framing risk minimization under performativity within a decision-theoretic framework to find equilibria where the model is optimal for the distribution it creates. This idea was also explored by Hardt et al. (2016) in strategic classification, a notable subtype of performative prediction. Subsequent research has focused on computing performative stable

(Mendler-Dünner et al., 2020) or performative optimal (Izzo et al., 2022) policies and developing related algorithms for online settings (Jagadeesan et al., 2022). For a more detailed review of the literature, see Section 1.1.

In performative prediction, the specific mechanism of the distribution shift is usually unknown. Previous work circumvents this issue in two ways: The first is to treat the performative prediction problem (2.2) as a zeroth order (derivative-free) optimization problem, where one only relies on samples drawn from the distributions $Q_{\theta_{t}}$ induced by iterations $\theta_{t}$ and solves the performative prediction problem without knowing the performative distribution map $\theta \mapsto Q_{\theta}$, i.e. the map of performative distribution induced by a predictor $\theta$ (Izzo et al., 2021; Miller et al., 2021). One drawback of this approach is its slow convergence: e.g. Izzo et al.'s algorithm relies on finite differences to approximate the gradient of the performative risk, so it suffers from the curse of dimensionality.

The second approach stipulates that each agent follows a (potentially misspecified) microfoundation model (Jang et al., 2022) and incorporates the anticipated agent responses into the optimization. This method leverages the fast convergence rates of the algorithm for performative risk minimization that benefit from full access to the distribution map (Hardt et al., 2016; Levanon and Rosenfeld, 2021; Cutler et al., 2021; Somerstep et al., 2023). However, the agent response model is often inaccurate (Lin and Zrnic, 2023), leading to incorrect distribution maps and preventing effective resolution of the performative prediction problem. We illustrate this issue in an example of strategic ordinary least squares (OLS) prediction in Example 2.1.

To address this issue, we propose an estimator for the microfoundation models of agent responses. Our approach complements the second approach; on the one hand, we alleviate the issues of misspecified agent response models by learning the microfoundations model from agent response data, and on the other hand, the white-box access to the distribution map allows the learner to take advantage of faster optimization algorithms for minimizing the performative risk. Another benefit of our approach is that it is well suited to more sophisticated learning algorithms (e.g. algorithms that enforce constraints (Maity et al., 2021; Somerstep et al., 2023)) that have no obvious zeroth order counterpart.

Our approach to estimate the microfoundation model is to assume that the agents' microfoundation is a utility maximization problem consisting of a (modeldependent) known benefit function $B_{f}$ and an unknown cost function $c$. A detailed exposition of our approach can be found in Section 3, where we develop an optimal
transport-based method to estimate the cost within a class of Bregman divergences. Our contributions are as follows:

1. We propose a method for estimating the cost function (within a class of Bregman divergences) of a general utility-maximizing microfoundation model. Our method relies on matching pre-model deployment and post-model deployment distributions with optimal transport.
2. We provide an analysis of identifiability in the estimation of the cost function, as well as rates of convergence of our proposed estimator.
3. We perform numerical experiments that both exhibit the performance of our methodology in estimating the cost and demonstrate its usefulness on a variety of down-stream tasks. We also demonstrate empirically that our methodology satisfies certain robustness properties with respect to misspecification of the benefit function.

### 1.1 Related works

The performative prediction problem was introduced by Perdomo et al. (2020). Much of the methodological focus in performative prediction is on locating performative stable or performative optimal solutions. To locate a stable solution, a paradigm of repeated retraining has been developed in multiple environments Mendler-Dünner et al. (2020); Drusvyatskiy and Xiao (2023). Furthermore, a line of prior work on this often utilizes zero'th order algorithms such as finite differences Izzo et al. $(2021,2022)$ or regret minimization (Jagadeesan et al., 2022; Dong et al., 2018; Chen et al., 2020). Other works instead assume white-box access to a pre-specified performative map (Levanon and Rosenfeld, 2021; Somerstep et al., 2023; Shavit et al., 2020; Lin and Zrnic, 2023) or make structural assumptions on the underlying data (e.g assuming all data is drawn from a location-scale family) (Miller et al., 2021). The work Tsirtsis et al. (2024) casts finding a performatively optimal model (given access to a performative map) as an optimal transport problem.
As pointed out in Lin and Zrnic (2023) such prespecified maps are often misspecified leading to erroneous results. We focus on correcting this by building a robust method to infer performative maps.
Originating with strategic classification Hardt et al. (2016); pre-specified models of performative maps are often at the sample level, and correspond to samples behaving as agents with strategic behavior. Strategic classification has been expanded in several directions: including models with causality Mendler-Dünner et al.

(2022); Horowitz and Rosenfeld (2023); Somerstep et al. (2023); Harris et al. (2022), models with opaque agent behavior Ghalme et al. (2021), the effects of strategic behavior on graph neural networks Eilat et al. (2023), models with reversed order of play Zrnic et al. (2022), PAC learning for strategic classification Sundaram et al. (2021), strategic ordinary least squares Shavit et al. (2020) and combinations of these (Levanon and Rosenfeld, 2022). Strategic behavior with an element of competition between agents has been used to model the behavior of content creators in socio-technical systems (Hron et al., 2023; Jagadeesan et al., 2023). The study of strategic behavior is not isolated to computer science; strategic behavior is the key ingredient to many micro-economic models of labor markets (Coate and Loury, 1993; Moro and Norman, 2003, 2004; Fang and Moro, 2011).

The common theme of strategic behavior is that each data sample is an agent that is assumed to maximize a cost-adjusted utility that depends on the model $\theta$; therefore, the performative map is implicitly determined by the agents' utility and cost. Our main contribution is a methodology that allows practitioners to infer agents' costs and utilities. Prior work on inferring performative maps is relatively light. The works of Mendler-Dünner et al. (2022); Lechner et al. (2023) assume that the aggregate manipulation structure is in a class of graphs $\mathcal{G}$ and infer the manipulation graph. Shavit et al. (2020) includes some focus on the inference of strategic responses, but only in the case of linear regression. Our methodology is applicable beyond these special cases and additionally allows for inference with both samples from the ex-ante and an ex-post distribution or samples from multiple ex-post distributions.
Inference of agent costs and utilities is often a crucial step in deploying accurate models in performative settings. For example, utilizing differentiable proxies to arg max, the authors of Levanon and Rosenfeld (2021) provide a framework for minimizing performative risk in a strategic environment. Unfortunately, if the strategic model is not specified correctly, then the resulting estimator of an optimal model will not be consistent (Lin and Zrnic, 2023). Our methodology allows for practitioners to utilize plug-in optimization frameworks with peace of mind.

## 2 Microfoundations for strategic prediction

We follow the performative prediction setting in (Perdomo et al., 2020, Section 5): at the microlevel, the agents are rational, i.e. they respond to a predictive model $\theta$ by choosing their best actions. Each agent is represented by a pair of attributes $Z=(X, Y) \in$

$$
\mathcal{Z}=\mathcal{X} \times \mathcal{Y}, \text { where } X \text { and } Y \text { are the covariates and the }
$$

outcome of an individual. Before agents are exposed to a model $\theta$ their attributes follow an ex-ante distribution $Z \sim P \in \Delta(\mathcal{Z})$ (where $\Delta(\mathcal{Z})$ is the set of probability measures over $\mathcal{Z}$ ), and, having been exposed to $\theta$, they strategically maximize their cost-adjusted utility that depends on $\theta$; i.e. in response to $\theta$ each agent updates their individual $Z$ via

$$
T_{\theta}(Z) \in \arg \max _{z^{\prime} \in \mathcal{Z}} B_{\theta}\left(z^{\prime}\right)-c\left(Z, z^{\prime}\right)
$$

Here, $B_{\theta}\left(z^{\prime}\right)$ encodes the benefit of the agent changing their attributes to $z^{\prime}$ when exposed to $\theta$, and $c$ is a cost function that encodes the burden of changing their attributes from $Z$ to $z^{\prime}$. Throughout, we will assume that $B_{\theta}(\cdot)$ is known, and $c(\cdot, \cdot)$ remains to be estimated. Often, the utility $B_{\theta}(\cdot)$ is simply the output of the learners predictive model (e.g. in standard strategic classification (Hardt et al., 2016)) or is a function of a learner controlled wage and output of the learners predictive model (e.g. in labor market models (Coate and Loury, 1993)). In either case, all information pertinent to the benefit function is known to the learner, which is why we focus on the case of known benefit functions and unknown costs. Additionally, we will demonstrate (cf. Sections 5 \& Appendix B) that our methodology correctly estimates $T_{\theta}(z)$ even if $B_{\theta}(z)$ is misspecified, (though the cost will not be estimated correctly).

We call $T_{\theta}$ the agents' response map. Due to the agents response to $\theta$, the distribution of attributes has now shifted to $Q_{\theta}=\left(T_{\theta}\right)_{\#} P$, which is the push-forward measure of $P$ through the agents' response $T_{\theta}$. We refer to this $Q_{\theta}$ as the performative distribution or expost distribution under the learner's action $\theta$. The map $\theta \mapsto Q_{\theta}$ is referred to as the performative distribution map or simply distribution map.
The microfoundation model in eq. (2.1) covers a variety of performative prediction problems, that includes strategic classification (Hardt et al., 2016), causal strategic classification (Miller et al., 2020; Levanon and Rosenfeld, 2021; Shavit et al., 2020; Somerstep et al., 2023), content creation (Hron et al., 2022), and micro-economic models of labor markets (Coate and Loury, 1993).

### 2.1 Importance of microfoundation inference for downstream tasks

Next, we cover two important use cases for estimating the agents microfoundations.
Performative risk minimization As a response to the distribution shift, the learner aims to learn a predictor that minimizes the performative risk which accounts for the agents' response:

$$
\min _{\theta \in \mathcal{F}} \operatorname{PR}(\theta), \operatorname{PR}(\theta) \triangleq \mathbb{E}_{Z \sim Q_{\theta}}[\ell(\theta ; Z)]
$$

where $\ell$ is the appropriate prediction loss. Previous methods for performative risk minimization incorporate an agents' microfoundation to anticipate the distribution shift (Hardt et al., 2016; Levanon and Rosenfeld, 2021; Somerstep et al., 2023). As we demonstrate in the following example, estimates obtained using a misspecified microfoundation can be arbitrarily poor.
Example 2.1 (Causal Strategic OLS (Shavit et al., 2020)). In a linear regression setting, we highlight the importance of estimating the cost. Consider an exante distribution $P$ of agents' profiles, where a typical sample point $(X, Y) \in \mathbb{R}^{d} \times \mathbb{R}$ satisfies the following: $X \sim \mathbf{N}\left(0, \mathbf{I}_{d}\right)$ and for an $\epsilon \sim \mathbf{N}\left(0, \sigma^{2}\right), \epsilon \perp$ $\perp X$ the $Y=X^{\top} \theta^{\star}+\epsilon$, for a $\theta^{\star} \in \mathbb{R}^{d}$. Once $a \theta \in \mathbb{R}^{d}$ is published, agents adjust their $X$ 's to maximize their benefit $B_{\theta}(X) \triangleq \theta^{\top} X$, while the $Y$ 's remain unchanged. Assuming that the true cost is $c\left(x, x^{\prime}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(x-x^{\prime}\right)^{\top} M\left(x-x^{\prime}\right)$, where $M$ is a predetermined positive definite matrix, the true agent's response map and performative risk are

$$
\begin{aligned}
T_{\theta}(X) & =\arg \max _{x^{\prime}} \theta^{\top} x^{\prime}-\frac{1}{2}\left(X-x^{\prime}\right)^{\top} M\left(X-x^{\prime}\right) \\
& =X+M^{-1} \theta \\
P R(\theta) & =\mathbb{E}\left[\left\{Y-\theta^{\top} T_{\theta}(X)\right\}^{2}\right] \\
& =\sigma^{2}+\left\|\theta-\theta^{\star}\right\|_{2}^{2}+\left\{\theta^{\top} M^{-1} \theta\right\}^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

If the agents cost is misspecified to $\widetilde{c}\left(x, x^{\prime}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left\|x-x^{\prime}\right\|_{2}^{2}$, then by letting $M=\mathbb{L}_{d}$ in the equations (2.3) and (2.4) the learner anticipates the agents map and the corresponding performative risk as

$$
\widehat{T}_{\theta}(X)=X+\theta, \widehat{P R}(\theta)=\sigma^{2}+\left\|\theta-\theta^{\star}\right\|_{2}^{2}+\|\theta\|_{2}^{4}
$$

As we show in Lemma A. 1 that the learner who minimizes the wrongly anticipated $\widehat{P R}(\theta)$ decides on its optimizer $\hat{\theta}=\iota \theta^{\star}$ where $c$ is the only positive solution to equation $2\left\|\theta^{\star}\right\|_{2}^{2} c^{3}+c-1=0$. However, the true performance risk for such a $\hat{\theta}$ is suboptimal, since

$$
\begin{aligned}
& P R(\hat{\theta})-\min _{\theta} P R(\theta) \geq P R(\hat{\theta})-P R(0) \\
& \quad=\left\{(c-1)^{2}-1\}\left\|\theta^{\star}\right\|_{2}^{2}+c^{4}\left\{\theta^{\star \top} M^{-1} \theta^{\star}\right\}^{2}\right.
\end{aligned}
$$

can be arbitrarily large depending on $M$, and, even trivially predicting every response as $\hat{Y}=0^{\top} X=0$ has a better performative risk than $\hat{\theta}^{\top} X$. To mitigate this suboptimality, one must estimate the cost.

Enforcing long-term fairness: Beyond accuracy, the call for practitioners to deploy socially responsible models in performative settings has grown; models are generally considered socially responsible if they either induce improvement (encourage increase of agent outcomes $Y$ ) or treat agents fairly post distribution
shift (Miller et al., 2020; D'Amour et al., 2020; Estornell et al., 2021; Liu et al., 2018; Somerstep et al., 2024). In either case, if one wishes to meet some definition of responsibility, inference on the individuals' response to models (e.g the cost for an individual to improve $Y$ in response to $\theta$ ) is a necessary step.

## 3 Learning agents' response

The first sticking point in agent cost estimation is a question identifiability: what class of costs can be learned if one only observes a finite number of samples over a finite number of model deployments? Note that estimating a general bivariate cost function $c\left(z, z^{\prime}\right)$ is conceptually impossible when we have access to samples from only finitely many ex-post distributions $\left\{Q_{\theta_{i}}, i=\right.$ $1, \ldots, m\}$, in addition to the ex-ante distribution $P$; even if we assume that we know the exact distributions. From the equality $Q_{\theta_{i}}=\left(T_{\theta_{i}}\right)_{\#} P$, we can only know the finite number of actions $\left\{T_{\theta_{i}}(z) ; i=1, \ldots, m\right\}$ by the agent with the ex-ante attribute $z$ when exposed to the models $\theta_{1}, \ldots, \theta_{m}$. Thus, from the first-order condition of (2.1), which is

$$
\partial B_{\theta}\left(T_{\theta}(z)\right)-\partial_{2} c\left(z, T_{\theta}(z)\right)=0
$$

one can only evaluate the partial derivative of the cost at the points $\left\{\left(z, T_{\theta_{i}}(z)\right), i=1, \ldots, m\right\}$ and for a given $z$ it is impossible to evaluate $z^{\prime} \mapsto \partial_{2} c\left(z, z^{\prime}\right)$ beyond these points.

### 3.1 Agents' cost as Bregman Divergence

In light of the non-identifiability of the generic cost $c\left(z, z^{\prime}\right)$ from a finite number of ex-ante distributions, we estimate the agents' cost within a class of Bregman divergences (Bregman, 1967):

$$
c_{\varphi}\left(z, z^{\prime}\right) \triangleq \varphi\left(z^{\prime}\right)-\varphi(z)-\nabla \varphi(z)^{\top}\left(z^{\prime}-z\right)
$$

where $\varphi: \mathbb{R}^{d} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ is a strictly convex Bregman potential. This assumption mitigates the problem of nonidentifiability of the cost $c$ for finitely many deployed models $\theta$, because estimating $c\left(z, z^{\prime}\right)$ is reduced to estimating $\varphi(z)$, thus eliminating the joint dependency of $\left(z, z^{\prime}\right)$. In addition to making it possible to estimate the cost function, the Bregman divergence specification allows us to set the problem of cost estimation in an optimal transport framework. Furthermore, the class of Bregman divergences is broad and often subsumes classes of costs that are studied in other works. For example: Perdomo et al., 2020, Section 5.2, Hardt et al., 2016, Section 5.1 considers a simple $\left\|z-z^{\prime}\right\|_{2}^{2}$ cost, which is a special case of Bregman divergence with potential $\|z\|_{2}^{2}$; in Liu et al. (2023) the cost is $c\left(z, z^{\prime}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(z-z^{\prime}\right)^{\top} A\left(z-z^{\prime}\right)$ for some positive definite matrix $A$, which is a special case of Bregman divergence with potential $\varphi(z)=\frac{1}{2} z^{\top} A z$; Other parametric

restrictions imposed on distribution maps in the strategic learning literature include Izzo et al. (2021); Miller et al. (2021); Jagadeesan et al. (2022).
As the divergence is induced by its potential $\varphi$, from now on we focus on estimating $\varphi$. We consider two scenarios depending on whether a sample from the ex-ante distribution $P$ is available or not.

### 3.2 Learning from ex-ante and ex-post distributions

First, we assume that the learner has random samples $\mathcal{D}_{0} \triangleq\left\{z_{0, i}\right\}_{i=1}^{n o} \stackrel{\text { iid }}{=} P$ from the ex ante distribution and $\mathcal{D}_{\theta_{k}} \triangleq\left\{z_{k, i}\right\}_{i=1}^{n o} \stackrel{\text { iid }}{=} Q_{\theta_{k}}$ from $m$ ex-post distributions $Q_{\theta_{1}}, \ldots, Q_{\theta_{m}}$ related to the agents' response to $m$ prediction models $\theta_{1}, \ldots, \theta_{m}$. Let $\widehat{P}$ and $\widehat{Q}_{\theta_{k}}$ 's be the empirical counterparts of $P$ and $Q_{\theta_{k}}$ 's. We estimate $\varphi$ by solving

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \underset{\varphi \in \Phi_{\mathrm{cva}}}{\arg \min } \min _{\mu \in \Delta(\mathcal{Z})} \mathscr{L}\left(\mu, \widehat{\varphi}, \widehat{P}, \widehat{Q}_{\theta_{1}}, \ldots, \widehat{Q}_{\theta_{m}}\right) \\
& \text { with } \mathscr{L}\left(\mu, \varphi, P, Q_{\theta_{1}}, \ldots, Q_{\theta_{m}}\right) \triangleq \\
& W_{2}^{2}\left(\mu,(\nabla \varphi)_{\#} P\right)+\sum_{k=1}^{m} W_{2}^{2}\left(\mu,\left(\nabla \varphi-\nabla B_{\theta_{k}}\right)_{\#} Q_{\theta_{k}}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

$\Phi_{\text {cva }}$ a class of convex potential functions, $W_{2}$ the 2-Wasserstein distance and $T_{\#} P$ denotes the pushforward measure of $P$ through the map $T$.

The problem (3.1) is motivated by a first-order characterization of the micro-level responses in (2.1); for a generic $\theta$ :

$$
\begin{aligned}
& T_{\theta}(z)=\arg \max _{z^{\prime} \in \mathcal{Z}}\left\{B_{\theta}\left(z^{\prime}\right)-c_{\varphi^{*}}\left(z, z^{\prime}\right)\right\} \\
& \text { or, } \nabla \varphi^{*} \circ T_{\theta}(z)-\nabla B_{\theta} \circ T_{\theta}(z)=\nabla \varphi^{*}(z)
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\varphi^{*}$ is the (unknown) Bregman potential for the cost. We recall that $\left(T_{\theta}\right)_{\#} P=Q_{\theta}$, which implies the distributions $\left(\nabla \varphi^{*}-\nabla B_{\theta}\right)_{\#} Q_{\theta}$ and $\left(\nabla \varphi^{*}\right)_{\#} P$ must be identical:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left\{\left(\nabla \varphi^{*}-\nabla B_{\theta}\right) \circ T_{\theta}\right\}_{\#} P \stackrel{\mathrm{~d}}{=}\left(\nabla \varphi^{*}\right)_{\#} P \quad(\text { from (3.2)) } \\
& \Longrightarrow\left(\nabla \varphi^{*}-\nabla B_{\theta}\right)_{\#} Q_{\theta} \stackrel{\mathrm{d}}{=}\left(\nabla \varphi^{*}\right)_{\#} P
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\stackrel{\mathrm{d}}{=}$ denotes equality in distributions. It follows that for $\theta_{1} \ldots \theta_{m},\left(\nabla \varphi^{*}\right)_{\#} P,\left(\nabla \varphi^{*}-\nabla B_{\theta_{1}}\right)_{\#} Q_{\theta_{1}}$, $\ldots,\left(\nabla \varphi^{*}-\nabla B_{\theta_{m}}\right)_{\#} Q_{\theta_{m}}$, are all identically distributed. In optimization (3.1) we estimate $\varphi^{*}$ by exploiting this equality in the distribution, where we minimize the 2-Wasserstein variance. We use the (2-) Wasserstein distance in (3.1) because agent responses may not have common support, and it also allows us to leverage algorithms for fast computation of Wasserstein barycenters to solve (3.1) in a block coordinate descent algorithm (cf. see Tseng (2001) for details on convergence). We summarize our method in Algorithm 1.

## Algorithm 1 Aligning agent responses

1: Input: initial estimate $\widehat{\varphi}$ and $\widehat{P}, \widehat{Q}_{\theta_{1}}, \ldots \widehat{Q}_{\theta_{m}}$
2: repeat
3: Compute the barycenter:

$$
\widehat{\mu} \leftarrow \arg \min _{\mu} \mathscr{L}\left(\mu, \widehat{\varphi}, \widehat{P}, \widehat{Q}_{\theta_{1}}, \ldots, \widehat{Q}_{\theta_{m}}\right)
$$

4: Update the Bregman potential:

$$
\widehat{\varphi} \leftarrow \arg \min _{\varphi \in \Phi_{\mathrm{cva}}} \mathscr{L}\left(\widehat{\mu}, \varphi, \widehat{P}, \widehat{Q}_{\theta_{1}}, \ldots, \widehat{Q}_{\theta_{m}}\right)
$$

5: until converged

Although it is often desirable to estimate the $\varphi$ nonparametrically, for a higher dimensional $Z=(X, Y)$ one may further restrict $\varphi$ to a suitable parametric class of potential functions and find the optimal $\widehat{\varphi}$ within that class. We provide an example of such a parametric specification in Section 5.2, where we assume that the cost function is quadratic, i.e. $c\left(z, z^{\prime}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(z-z^{\prime}\right)^{\top} \mathbf{M}\left(z-z^{\prime}\right)$ for a positive definite $\mathbf{M}$, in which case the potentials are parameterized as $\varphi(z)=\frac{1}{2} z^{\top} \mathbf{M} z$.

### 3.3 Learning from ex-post distributions

Assume that only observations of the ex post (performative) distributions $Q_{\theta_{k}}$ 's are available. Similarly to before, the first-order optimality conditions of the (2.1) show that the push-forwards of the agent responses $Q_{\theta_{k}}$ under $\nabla B_{\theta_{k}}-\nabla \varphi, k \in[m]$ are identical, which suggests we estimate $\varphi$ aligning the pushforward distributions of the agent responses under the $\left(\nabla \varphi-\nabla B_{\theta_{k}}\right.$ )'s:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \widehat{\varphi} \in \underset{\varphi \in \Phi_{\mathrm{cva}}}{\arg \min } \min _{\mu \in \Delta(\mathcal{Z})} \overline{\mathscr{L}}\left(\mu, \varphi, \widehat{Q}_{\theta_{1}}, \ldots, \widehat{Q}_{\theta_{m}}\right) \\
& \text { where } \overline{\mathscr{L}}\left(\mu, \varphi, Q_{\theta_{1}}, \ldots, Q_{\theta_{m}}\right) \text { is defined as } \\
& =\sum_{k=1}^{m} W_{2}^{2}\left(\mu,\left(\nabla \varphi-\nabla B_{\theta_{k}}\right)_{\#} Q_{\theta_{k}}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

## 4 Theoretical analysis

Identifiability of the cost function: A crucial step in analyzing the estimated cost is to verify whether it is identifiable from the proposed algorithms. More specifically, we investigate whether the potential functions obtained from (3.1) and (3.4) induce a Bergman divergence identical to $c_{\varphi^{*}}$ (the true cost function), when the empirical distributions $\widehat{P}, \widehat{Q}_{\theta}, \ldots, \widehat{Q}_{\theta_{m}}$ are substituted by their respective population versions $P, Q_{\theta}, \ldots, Q_{\theta_{m}}$. Since a Bergman divergence remains identical under any linear adjustment to its inducing potential, we verify whether $\Phi^{*} \triangleq\left\{\varphi^{*}(z)+\alpha_{0}+\alpha_{1}^{\top} z\right\}$

contains

$$
\begin{cases}\underset{\varphi \in \Phi_{\text {cya }}}{\arg \min } \min _{\mu \in \Delta(\mathcal{Z})} \mathscr{L}\left(\mu, \varphi, P, Q_{\theta_{1}}, \ldots, Q_{\theta_{m}}\right) & \text { (ex-ante) } \\ \underset{\varphi \in \Phi_{\text {cya }}}{\arg \min } \min _{\mu \in \Delta(\mathcal{Z})} \widetilde{\mathscr{L}}\left(\mu, \varphi, Q_{\theta_{1}}, \ldots, Q_{\theta_{m}}\right) & \text { (ex-post) }\end{cases}
$$

To verify this, we first observe that the objectives of (4.1) are identical to zero when $\varphi=\varphi^{\star}$, as we argue after (3.1) that $\left(\nabla \varphi^{\star}\right)_{\#} P,\left(\nabla \varphi^{\star}-\nabla B_{\theta}\right)_{\#} Q_{\theta}$, $\ldots,\left(\nabla \varphi^{\star}-\nabla B_{\theta_{m}}\right)_{\#} Q_{\theta_{m}}$ are identically distributed. Since these objectives are non-negative, it is clear that they must be zero at their minimum value, which further implies that for any minimizer $\tilde{\varphi}$, all $m+1$ distributions used to calculate the barycenter distances must be identical to the barycenters. In the following lemma, we make use of this observation to derive an equivalence condition to verify whether the cost is identifiable.
Theorem 4.1. In the ex-ante problem, denote the transportation maps from the barycenter to the measures $P, Q_{\theta}, \ldots Q_{\theta_{m}}$ as $T_{0}, T_{1}, \ldots, T_{m}$, and similarly, in (ex-post), denote them as $T_{1}, \ldots, T_{m}$. Then an equivalent condition for (4.1) is that all conservative solutions $h$ (i.e. can be written as the derivative of a convex function) of the following equations are constant functions.

$$
\begin{cases}h \circ T_{0}(z)=\cdots=h \circ T_{m}(z) \text { for all } z & \text { (ex-ante) } \\ h \circ T_{1}(z)=\cdots=h \circ T_{m}(z) & \text { for all } z \quad \text { (ex-post) }\end{cases}
$$

In practice, this condition can be used to verify whether the cost is uniquely identified from the available dataset. As an example, consider the following corollary.
Corollary 4.2. With access to the ex-ante distribution $P$ assume that only one performative distribution $Q_{\theta_{1}}$ is observed. If $B_{\theta_{1}}$ is strictly concave with a finite maximizer, then the condition in Theorem 4.1 is satisfied. Thus, the cost function is identified only from these two distributions.

Rate of convergence for cost estimation: In addition to identifiability, we also establish a convergence rate for our proposed estimator using two distributions. Specifically, we estimate $\nabla \varphi$ within a parametric class $\left\{\psi_{\gamma}: \gamma \in \Gamma\right\}$ using samples from two distributions: an ex-ante $(P)$ and a single ex-post $\left(Q_{\theta}\right)$. In this case, the loss utilized to estimate $\gamma$ in Algorithm 1 is

$$
\mathbf{L}(\Pi, \gamma) \triangleq \int \Pi\left(d z, d z^{\prime}\right)\left\|\psi_{\gamma}(z)-\psi_{\gamma}\left(z^{\prime}\right)+\nabla B_{\theta}\left(z^{\prime}\right)\right\|_{2}^{2}
$$

and the population value $\left(\gamma^{\star}\right)$ and the estimated value $(\widehat{\gamma})$ of the parameter can be calculated as

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \gamma^{\star} \triangleq \arg \min _{\gamma} \min _{\Pi \in \Delta\left(P, Q_{\theta}\right)} \mathbf{L}(\Pi, \gamma) \\
& \widehat{\gamma} \triangleq \arg \min _{\gamma} \min _{\Pi \in \Delta\left(\widehat{P}, \widehat{Q}_{\theta}\right)} \mathbf{L}(\Pi, \gamma)
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\widehat{P}$ and $\widehat{Q}_{\theta}$ are the empirical counterparts of $P$ and $Q_{\theta}$, and $\Delta(\mu, \nu)$ is the set of probability measures on
$\mathcal{Z} \times \mathcal{Z}$ with marginals $\mu$ and $\nu$. In the following theorem, we establish an $\ell_{2}$ convergence rate between $\widehat{\gamma}$ and $\gamma^{\star}$ in the case where the OT loss used for cost estimation satisfies a strong convexity assumption. Note that this strong convexity assumption implies that we are also assuming that the cost is identifiable.
Theorem 4.3. Suppose that $P$ and $Q_{\theta}$ are compactly supported on $\mathbb{R}^{d}$ and are absolutely continuous with respect to the Lebesgue measure with bounded second moments. Denote $\widehat{P}$ and $\widehat{Q}_{\theta}$ as their empirical counterparts, each calculated using $n$ iid samples. Furthermore, assume that both $\gamma \mapsto \min _{\Pi \in \Delta\left(P, Q_{\theta}\right)} \mathbf{L}(\Pi, \gamma)$ and $\gamma \mapsto \min _{\Pi \in \Delta\left(\widehat{P}, \widehat{Q}_{\theta}\right)} \mathbf{L}(\Pi, \gamma)$ are strongly convex. Then there exists a $K>0$ such that

$$
\mathbb{E}\left[\left\|\widehat{\gamma}-\gamma^{\star}\right\|_{2}^{2}\right] \leq K n^{-2 / d}
$$

This rate was established using convergence results for the empirical Wasserstein distance from Manole and Niles-Weed (2024, Theorem 2). Extending the upper bound in (4.4) to multiple ex-post distributions $Q_{\theta_{1}}, \ldots, Q_{\theta_{m}}$ or to nonidentical sample sizes for exante and ex-post distributions is possible, but, to the best of our knowledge, similar convergence results for the empirical Wasserstein distance that we may require are not available in the literature and we leave this for future work.

Impact of estimating the cost. Having estimated the $\widehat{\varphi}$, we can plug it in eq. (3.2) and estimate the response map from the equation

$$
\nabla \widehat{\varphi}\left(\widehat{T}_{\theta}(z)\right)-\nabla B_{\theta}\left(\widehat{T}_{\theta}(x)\right)=\nabla \widehat{\varphi}(x)
$$

which is then used in the performative loss function to estimate the performative optimal $(\mathrm{PO})$ solution:

$$
\widehat{\theta}=\arg \min _{\theta} \mathbb{E}_{P_{n}}\left[\ell\left(\theta, \widehat{T}_{\theta}(Z)\right)\right]
$$

To understand the comparison of $\operatorname{PR}(\widehat{\theta})$ against the $\min _{\theta} \operatorname{PR}(\theta)$ we recall the analysis in Lin and Zrnic (2023); especially Theorem 2. They decompose the risk-difference as

$$
\operatorname{PR}(\widehat{\theta})-\min _{\theta} \operatorname{PR}(\theta) \leq 2(\text { MisspErr }+ \text { StatErr })
$$

The first term is the error due to misspecification in our performative response map, often depending on the problem at hand and users' choice of the class of potential functions. The second term is a statistical error in estimating this response map. For a parametric specification of $\varphi$ we establish a rate of convergence $\mathcal{O}_{P}\left(n^{-1 / d}\right)$ for the said parameters ( $c f$. Theorem 4.3). Under standard regularity conditions (e.g. smoothness of the loss function and response map) one can understand that the statistical error will have the same $\mathcal{O}_{P}\left(n^{-2 / d}\right)$ rate of convergence.

## 5 Experiments

In this section, we demonstrate the effectiveness, robustness, and competitiveness of our method in semisynthetic setups. We use real data distributions as the ex-ante distributions and simulate agents' strategic behavior as utility-maximizing, consistent with (2.1).
Dataset: We use the same credit scoring dataset from Perdomo et al. (2020), which is publicly available on Kaggle (Cukierski, 2011). The performative prediction framework is particularly relevant in the credit scoring context, as individuals may face restricted access to credit once a predictive model is deployed by a credit bureau. To counter these constraints, agents adapt their behavior to manipulate the system after a credit predictor is introduced. In this dataset, the target variable is a default indicator ( $Y=$ SeriousDlqin2yrs), equal to one if an individual is 90 days delinquent or worse, and zero otherwise. Explanatory variables include metrics such as the total balance on credit cards and personal lines of credit, divided by the total credit limits ( $X=$ RevolvingUtilizationOfUnsecuredLines).

To estimate $\varphi$ in the uni-dimensional case with one ex-ante distribution and one ex-post distribution, we use a non-parametric estimator for $\varphi^{\prime}$. Specifically, $\varphi^{\prime}$ is estimated via monotonic (isotonic) regression and subsequently integrated to estimate $\varphi$. ### 5.2 Minimizing the performative risk

In this subsection, we apply our method to minimize the performative risk. We work in a multidimensional setup in which $X$ is composed of RevolvingUtilizationOfUnsecuredLines, DebtRatio (monthly debt payments divided by monthly gross income), Monthly income, and a constant representing the intercept. To simplify things, we consider all the features in $X$ to be performative and assume a linear benefit with a quadratic cost structure as in Example 2.1. To obtain ex-ante and ex-post data we publish a set of classifiers $\left\{\theta_{0}, \cdots, \theta_{K-1}\right\}$ randomly sampled from a Gaussian distribution centered around the optimal classifier in the ex-ante distribution $P$. We then estimate $M$ using Algorithm 1 where the minimization step over the set of all matrices is done using the Cholesky decomposition $M=L L^{\top}$ by optimizing for $L$ over the set of lower triangular matrices. ## 6 Summary and discussion

We propose algorithms to infer the performative distribution shift map in settings where samples are from strategic agents. Each agent responds to a model $\theta$ by solving $\arg \max _{z^{\prime}} B_{\theta}\left(z^{\prime}\right)-c_{\varphi}\left(z^{\prime}, z\right)$, where $B_{\theta}(\cdot)$ is a known benefit function and $c_{\varphi}(\cdot, \cdot)$ is an unknown cost induced by the Bregman potential $\varphi$, whose structure offers analytical convenience without sacrificing much generality. Our key method estimates the gradient of the Bregman potential $\nabla \varphi$ by aligning ex-ante and ex-post distributions using optimal transport. Our experiments show that the method is effective and robust to misspecifications in the benefit function $B_{\theta}(\cdot)$.
Performative prediction remains highly relevant in ML research and is applicable in a broad range of areas. Accurate knowledge of performative microfoundations is crucial for the deployment of effective and socially responsible models. Our method of learning agent response maps can make such deployment more accessible in strategic prediction problems, allowing practitioners to use fast-converging algorithms that require these response maps without fear of misspecification. While our paper focuses on prediction problems with strategic agents, learning distribution shifts in broader performative prediction problems, potentially involving nonstrategic agents, is an important question for future research and is beyond the scope of this paper.

## A Supplementary proofs

Lemma A.1. The misspecified performative risk $\widehat{P R}(\theta)=\sigma^{2}+\left\|\theta-\theta^{*}\right\|_{2}^{2}+\|\theta\|_{2}^{4}$ in Example 2.1 is minimized at $\hat{\theta}=c \theta^{*}$, where $c$ is the only positive solution to equation $2\left\|\theta^{*}\right\|_{2}^{2} c^{3}+c-1=0$.

Proof of Lemma A.1. The misspecified performative risk and its first-order for its minimization are

$$
\begin{gathered}
\widehat{\mathrm{PR}}(\theta)=\sigma^{2}+\left\|\theta-\theta^{*}\right\|_{2}^{2}+\|\theta\|_{2}^{4} \\
\nabla_{\theta} \widehat{\mathrm{PR}}(\theta)=2\left(\theta-\theta^{*}\right)+4\|\theta\|_{2}^{2} \theta=0 \\
\Longrightarrow\left\{1+2\|\theta\|_{2}^{2}\right\} \theta=\theta^{*} \text { or, } \theta=c \theta^{*}
\end{gathered}
$$

for some $0<c \leq 1$. It remains to optimize over $c \in(0,1]$. Letting $\theta=c \theta^{*}$ in $\widehat{\mathrm{PR}}(\theta)$ we obtain

$$
\widehat{\operatorname{PR}}\left(c \theta^{*}\right)=\sigma^{2}+(c-1)^{2}\left\|\theta^{*}\right\|_{2}^{2}+c^{4}\left\|\theta^{*}\right\|_{2}^{4}=\sigma^{2}+\left\|\theta^{*}\right\|_{2}^{2}\left\{(c-1)^{2}+c^{4}\left\|\theta^{*}\right\|_{2}^{2}\right\}
$$

and at its minimum the following first-order condition is satisfied:

$$
\left\|\theta^{*}\right\|_{2}^{2}\left\{2(c-1)+4 c^{3}\left\|\theta^{*}\right\|_{2}^{2}\right\}=0 \text { or, } 2\left\|\theta^{*}\right\|_{2}^{2} c^{3}+c-1=0
$$

What remains to be seen is whether the above equation has a solution in the interval $(0,1]$. This is evident from the following observation: for $f(c) \triangleq 2\left\|\theta^{*}\right\|_{2}^{2} c^{3}+c-1$ we see that

$$
f(0)=-1<0, f(1)=2\left\|\theta^{*}\right\|_{2} \geq 0, \text { and } f^{\prime}(c)=6\left\|\theta^{*}\right\|_{2}^{2} c^{2}+1>0
$$

Since $\theta$ is continuous and strictly increasing, we conclude that there is only one root of $f(c)=0$. Furthermore, from $f(0)<0 \leq f(1)$ we conclude that the root is in the interval $(0,1]$. This proves the lemma.

Proof of Theorem 4.1. We shall only prove the lemma for (ex-ante). The proof for (ex-post) is identical. As $T_{0}, T_{1}, \ldots, T_{m}$ are maps from the barycenter measure to $P, Q_{\theta_{1}}, \ldots Q_{\theta_{m}}$ in (4.1) and these measures are identical for the optimum $\varphi$, the barycenter problem must satisfy

$$
W_{2}^{2}\left(\mu,(\nabla \varphi)_{\#} P\right)+\sum_{k=1}^{m} W_{2}^{2}\left(\mu,\left(\nabla \varphi-\nabla B_{\theta_{k}}\right)_{\#} Q_{\theta_{k}}\right)=0
$$

and thus each of the Wasserstein are zero. This leads to

$$
z=(\nabla \varphi) \circ T_{0}(z)=\left(\nabla \varphi-\nabla B_{\theta_{1}}\right) \circ T_{1}(z)=\cdots=\left(\nabla \varphi-\nabla B_{\theta_{m}}\right) \circ T_{m}(z)
$$

To realize this, let us focus on the first Wasserstein distance: $W_{2}^{2}\left(\mu,(\nabla \varphi)_{\#} P\right)=0$, which implies that $\nabla \varphi$ is a measure-preserving push-forward map from $P$ to $\mu$. Furthermore, $\nabla \varphi$ is conservative (a derivative of a convex function). Now, since we used the quadratic cost $\|\cdot\|_{2}^{2}$ in our optimal transport, it follows from Brenier's theorem that $\nabla \varphi$ is an optimal transport map from $P$ to $\mu$. Furthermore, $T_{0}$ is the optimal transport map from $\mu$ to $P$. Thus, a combination of them is the identity map: $z=(\nabla \varphi) \circ T_{0}(z)$. We can use similar arguments for $W_{2}^{2}\left(\mu,\left(\nabla \varphi-\nabla B_{\theta_{k}}\right)_{\#} Q_{\theta_{k}}\right)=0$ to conclude: $z=\left(\nabla \varphi-\nabla B_{\theta_{k}}\right) \circ T_{k}(z)$
The equation (A.6) reduces to the following equivalent condition that

$$
(\nabla \varphi) \circ T_{0}(z)=\left(\nabla \varphi-\nabla B_{\theta_{1}}\right) \circ T_{1}(z)=\cdots=\left(\nabla \varphi-\nabla B_{\theta_{m}}\right) \circ T_{m}(z)
$$

The solutions of the above equations are unique up to a constant addition is equivalent to $\nabla \varphi$ being unique up to a constant addition. Thus, the cost is unique if and only if $\nabla \varphi \in\left\{\nabla \varphi^{\star}+\alpha\right\} \triangleq \mathcal{G}$. We write the homogeneous equation to (A.7)

$$
h \circ T_{0}(z)=h \circ T_{1}(z)=\cdots=h \circ T_{m}(z)
$$

and define the space of all its solutions as $\mathcal{H}$. Note that for any $g \in \mathcal{G}, h \in \mathcal{H}$ and $t \in \mathbb{R}$ we have $g+t h \in \mathcal{G}$, because for any $k \in[m]$ we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left(g+t h-\nabla B_{f_{k}}\right) \circ T_{k}(z) & =\left(g-\nabla B_{f_{k}}\right) \circ T_{k}(z)+t h \circ T_{k}(z) \\
& =g \circ T_{0}(z)+t h \circ T_{0}(z)
\end{aligned}
$$

Thus, $\mathcal{G}=\left\{\nabla \varphi^{\star}(z)+\alpha, \alpha \in \mathbb{R}^{d}\right\}$ if and only if all the functions in $\mathcal{H}$ are constant.
Proof of Corollary 4.2. Since there is only one $Q_{\theta_{1}}$ in addition to $P$, the optimization is reduced to

$$
\min _{\varphi \in \Phi_{\text {cva }}} \min _{\varphi \in \Delta(\mathcal{Z})} W_{2}^{2}\left(\mu,(\nabla \varphi)_{\#} P\right)+W_{2}^{2}\left(\mu,\left(\nabla \varphi-\nabla B_{\theta_{1}}\right)_{\#} Q_{\theta_{1}}\right)
$$

In case of barycenter with two distributions, the optimization simplifies to

$$
\min _{\varphi \in \Phi_{\text {cva }}} W_{2}^{2}\left((\nabla \varphi)_{\#} P,\left(\nabla \varphi-\nabla B_{\theta_{1}}\right)_{\#} Q_{\theta_{1}}\right)
$$

At the optimum $\nabla \varphi$ the objective is zero and hence $(\nabla \varphi)_{\#} P$ and $\left(\nabla \varphi-\nabla B_{\theta_{1}}\right)_{\#} Q_{\theta_{1}}$ are equal to the barycenter. Let $T_{0}$ and $T_{1}$ be the optimal transport map from the barycenter to the distributions $P$ to $Q_{\theta_{1}}$. Then, we need to verify that the equation

$$
g\left(T_{0}(z)\right)=g\left(T_{1}(z)\right) \text { or, equivalently } g(z)=g\left(T_{1} \circ T_{0}^{-1}(z)\right)
$$

are trivial. Here, $T=T_{1} \circ T_{0}^{-1}$ is the optimal transport map from $P$ to $Q_{\theta_{1}}$, which, by the first order condition of (2.1) satisfies

$$
\nabla \varphi \circ T(z)=\nabla \varphi(z)-\nabla B_{\theta_{1}}(z)
$$

We just need to prove that the only solutions for the equation

$$
g(T(z))=g(z)
$$

is constant solutions. According to (A.10) we have

$$
g(z)=g\left(T^{n}(z)\right), \quad T^{n}(z) \triangleq \underbrace{T \circ \cdots \circ T}_{n \text { times }}(z)
$$

As (A.9) is a first-order condition for $T(z)=\arg \max _{z^{\prime}} B_{\theta_{1}}\left(z^{\prime}\right)-d_{\varphi^{\star}}\left(z, z^{\prime}\right)$ we notice that $T$ is a proximal gradient ascend step for the strictly concave function $B_{\theta_{1}}$. Thus, for any $z$ we have $T^{n}(z) \rightarrow z^{\star} \triangleq \arg \max _{z^{\prime}} B_{\theta_{1}}\left(z^{\prime}\right)$ as $n \rightarrow \infty$. This and (A.11) implies

$$
g(z)=g\left(z^{\star}\right) \text { for all } z
$$

This implies $g$ is a constant function, which completes the proof.

Proof of Theorem 4.3. Let us denote the $\Pi_{\gamma}^{\star}$ and $\widehat{\Pi}_{\gamma}$ as the optimal couplings defined as:

$$
\Pi_{\gamma}^{\star}=\arg \min _{\Pi \in \Delta\left(P, Q_{\theta}\right)} \mathbf{L}(\Pi, \gamma), \quad \widehat{\Pi}_{\gamma}=\arg \min _{\Pi \in \Delta\left(\widehat{P}, \widehat{Q}_{\theta}\right)} \mathbf{L}(\Pi, \gamma)
$$

which are unique (Villani, 2009). Using the local strong convexity of $\mathbf{L}\left(\Pi_{\gamma}^{\star}, \gamma\right)$ at $\gamma^{\star}$ and local strong convexity of $\mathbf{L}\left(\widehat{\Pi}_{\gamma}, \gamma\right)$ at $\widehat{\gamma}$ we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathbf{L}\left(\Pi_{\widehat{\gamma}}^{\star}, \widehat{\gamma}\right)-\mathbf{L}\left(\Pi_{\gamma^{\star}}^{\star}, \gamma^{\star}\right) \geq \underbrace{\left\langle\widehat{\gamma}-\gamma^{\star}, \frac{d}{d \gamma} \mathbf{L}\left(\Pi_{\gamma^{\star}}^{\star}, \gamma^{\star}\right)\right\rangle}_{=0}+\frac{\kappa}{2}\left\|\widehat{\gamma}-\gamma^{\star}\right\|_{2}^{2} \\
& \mathbf{L}\left(\widehat{\Pi}_{\gamma^{\star}}, \gamma^{\star}\right)-\mathbf{L}\left(\widehat{\Pi}_{\widehat{\gamma}}, \widehat{\gamma}\right) \geq \underbrace{\left\langle\widehat{\gamma}-\gamma^{\star}, \frac{d}{d \gamma} \mathbf{L}\left(\widehat{\Pi}_{\widehat{\gamma}}, \widehat{\gamma}\right)\right\rangle}_{=0}+\frac{\kappa}{2}\left\|\widehat{\gamma}-\gamma^{\star}\right\|_{2}^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

We add the two equations to yield:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\kappa\|\widehat{\gamma}-\gamma^{\star}\|_{2}^{2} & \leq \mathbf{L}\left(\Pi_{\widehat{\gamma}}^{\star}, \widehat{\gamma}\right)-\mathbf{L}\left(\Pi_{\gamma^{\star}}^{\star}, \gamma^{\star}\right)+\mathbf{L}\left(\widehat{\Pi}_{\gamma^{\star}}, \gamma^{\star}\right)-\mathbf{L}\left(\widehat{\Pi}_{\widehat{\gamma}}, \widehat{\gamma}\right) \\
& =\left|\mathbf{L}\left(\Pi_{\widehat{\gamma}}^{\star}, \widehat{\gamma}\right)-\mathbf{L}\left(\widehat{\Pi}_{\widehat{\gamma}}, \widehat{\gamma}\right)\right|+\left|\mathbf{L}\left(\widehat{\Pi}_{\gamma^{\star}}, \gamma^{\star}\right)-\mathbf{L}\left(\Pi_{\gamma^{\star}}^{\star}, \gamma^{\star}\right)\right|
\end{aligned}
$$

We take an expectation over the randomness in $\widehat{P}$ and $\widehat{Q}_{\theta}$ to yield:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\kappa \mathbb{E}\left[\left\|\widehat{\gamma}-\gamma^{\star}\right\|_{2}^{2}\right] & \leq \mathbb{E}\left[\left|\mathbf{L}\left(\Pi_{\widehat{\gamma}}^{\star}, \widehat{\gamma}\right)-\mathbf{L}\left(\widehat{\Pi}_{\widehat{\gamma}}, \widehat{\gamma}\right)\right|\right]+\mathbb{E}\left[\left|\mathbf{L}\left(\widehat{\Pi}_{\gamma^{\star}}, \gamma^{\star}\right)-\mathbf{L}\left(\Pi_{\gamma^{\star}}^{\star}, \gamma^{\star}\right)\right|\right] \\
& \leq 2 \sup _{\gamma \in B_{\delta}\left(\gamma^{\star}\right)} \mathbb{E}\left[\left|\mathbf{L}\left(\Pi_{\gamma}^{\star}, \gamma\right)-\mathbf{L}\left(\widehat{\Pi}_{\gamma}, \gamma\right)\right|\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

where $B_{\delta}\left(\gamma^{\star}\right) \triangleq\left\{\gamma:\left\|\gamma-\gamma^{\star}\right\|_{2} \leq \delta\right\}$ for some $\delta>0$. Thus, the $\ell_{2}$ error for estimating the parameter is

$$
\mathbb{E}\left[\left\|\widehat{\gamma}-\gamma^{\star}\right\|_{2}^{2}\right] \leq \frac{2}{\kappa} \sup _{\gamma \in B_{\delta}\left(\gamma^{\star}\right)} \mathbb{E}\left[\left|\mathbf{L}\left(\Pi_{\gamma}^{\star}, \gamma\right)-\mathbf{L}\left(\widehat{\Pi}_{\gamma}, \gamma\right)\right|\right]
$$

Under the assumption that $P$ is compactly supported on $\mathcal{X}_{P}$ the superdomain $\widetilde{\mathcal{X}}_{P}$ defined below is also compactly supported:

$$
\widetilde{\mathcal{X}}_{P}=\left\{\psi_{\gamma}(x): x \in \mathcal{X}_{P}, \gamma \in B_{\delta}\left(\gamma^{\star}\right)\right\}
$$

Since $P$ is compactly supported, so it $Q_{\theta}$, as it follows the microfoundation. Defining $\mathcal{Y}$ as a support for $Q_{\theta}$, since $\mathcal{Y}$ the superdomain $\widetilde{\mathcal{Y}}$ is also compactly supported.

$$
\widetilde{\mathcal{Y}}=\left\{\psi_{\gamma}(y)-b_{\theta}(y): y \in \mathcal{Y}, \gamma \in B_{\delta}\left(\gamma^{\star}\right)\right\}
$$

Defining $\tilde{\psi}_{\gamma}(y)=\psi_{\gamma}(y)-b_{\theta}(y), \mu_{\gamma}=\left(\psi_{\gamma}\right)_{\#} P \in \Delta\left(\widetilde{\mathcal{X}}_{P}\right)$ and $\nu_{\gamma}=\left(\tilde{\psi}_{\gamma}\right)_{\#} Q_{\theta} \in \Delta(\widetilde{\mathcal{Y}})$ we notice

$$
\mathbf{L}\left(\Pi_{\gamma}^{\star}, \gamma\right)=W_{2}^{2}\left(\mu_{\gamma}, \nu_{\gamma}\right), \quad \mathbf{L}\left(\widehat{\Pi}_{\gamma}, \gamma\right)=W_{2}^{2}\left(\widehat{\mu}_{\gamma}, \widehat{\nu}_{\gamma}\right)
$$

where $\widehat{\mu}_{\gamma}$ and $\widehat{\nu}_{\gamma}$ are empirical measures of $\mu$ and $\nu$ :

$$
\widehat{\mu}_{\gamma}=\left(\psi_{\gamma}\right)_{\#} \widehat{P}, \quad \widehat{\nu}_{\gamma}=\left(\tilde{\psi}_{\gamma}\right)_{\#} \widehat{Q}_{\theta}
$$

Since both the supports $\widetilde{\mathcal{X}}_{P}$ and $\widetilde{\mathcal{Y}}$ are compact, we use the bound in Manole and Niles-Weed (2024, Theorem 2) (with $\alpha=2$ ) to obtain:

$$
\mathbb{E}\left[\left\|\widehat{\gamma}-\gamma^{\star}\right\|_{2}^{2}\right] \leq \frac{2}{\kappa} \sup _{\gamma \in B_{\delta}\left(\gamma^{\star}\right)} \mathbb{E}\left[\left|\mathbf{L}\left(\Pi_{\gamma}^{\star}, \gamma\right)-\mathbf{L}\left(\widehat{\Pi}_{\gamma}, \gamma\right)\right|\right] \leq \frac{2}{\kappa} C n^{-\frac{2}{3}}
$$

for some $C>0$. This completes the proof.

# B Multi-dimensional cost estimation with convex neural network 

Here, we work in the multi-dimensional case with an ex-ante distribution and one ex-post distribution. The $\nabla \varphi$ is estimated using a Single Layer Neural Network (SLNN). More specifically, we model the potential function $\varphi$ as a single hidden layer convex neural network:

$$
\varphi_{\gamma}(x)=\sum_{j=1}^{h} \delta_{j} \sigma\left(\omega_{j}^{\gamma} x+\kappa_{j}\right), \quad \gamma=(\Omega, \kappa, \delta), \Omega=\left\{\omega_{j} ; j \in[h]\right\} \in \mathbb{R}^{h \times d}, \kappa \in \mathbb{R}^{h}, \delta_{j} \geq 0
$$

where $\sigma$ is a strictly convex and increasing function. For this section, we use $\sigma(t)=\log \left(1+e^{t}\right)$.

Figure 5: Estimation error for the map $T_{\theta}$ in the multivariate case with a convex neural network.

For our experiment, we consider $x \in \mathbb{R}^{5}$ and five hidden units for the $\varphi_{\gamma}$. We use $\sqrt{ } \cdot$ as the benefit function. With more details, we consider the benefit function the benefit $B_{\theta}\left(x^{\prime}\right)=\sum_{j} \theta_{j} x_{j}^{\frac{1}{2}}$, where $\theta$ is a randomly generated vector with positive entries. We use 8 different random seeds and plot the average result. The unknown Bregman potential is $\varphi(x)=\frac{\sigma}{2}\|x\|^{2}$, implying $\nabla \varphi(x)=\sigma x$ (we assume $\sigma=.1$ ). The agents start with $X \sim P=\mathbf{N}\left(0, \mathbf{I}_{d}\right)$, and then change their values of $X$ by maximizing their net gain:

$$
T_{\theta}(X)=\arg \max _{x^{\prime}} B_{\theta}\left(x^{\prime}\right)-c_{\varphi}\left(X, x^{\prime}\right)
$$

where in this case $c_{\varphi}\left(X, x^{\prime}\right)=\sigma / 2\left\|X-x^{\prime}\right\|^{2}$. After we train the SLNN we get an estimate $\widehat{\varphi}$ and we estimate $T_{\theta}$ by

$$
\widehat{T}_{\theta}(X)=\arg \max _{x^{\prime}} B_{\theta}\left(x^{\prime}\right)-c_{\widehat{\varphi}}\left(X, x^{\prime}\right)
$$

In Figure 5, we compare the error in the estimation of $T_{\theta}$ for two benefit functions: $\sum_{j} \theta_{j} x_{j}^{\frac{1}{2}}$, which is well specified, and $\sum_{j} \theta_{j} \log \left(x_{j}\right)$, which is misspecified. In both cases, we see an improved estimation for $T_{\theta}$ for a larger sample size, which again exhibits the robustness in estimating $T_{\theta}$ despite having a misspecified benefit.

# C Experiments
## C. 1 Model training procedure in Section 5.2

In this experiment, agents can manipulate their features once a logistic regression classifier, $\theta=(\alpha, \beta)$, is published. In this context, $\alpha$ is the intercept term while $\beta$ is the slope. We assume ${ }^{2} B_{\theta}(x)=|\beta|^{\top} x=-\beta^{\top} x$ (Perdomo et al., 2020) and consider the case of parametric cost estimation with $\varphi(x)=\frac{1}{2} x^{\top} M x$ where $M$ is a positive definite matrix to be learned. As we show in (2.3), agents' response in this setting is $T_{\theta}(x)=X-M^{-1} \beta$. For the main experiment, we assume $M=0.1 * I_{3}$ and include more results in Appendix C.2.
To apply our method to the problem of minimizing the performative risk, we publish a set of classifiers $\left\{\theta_{0}, \cdots, \theta_{K-1}\right\}$ randomly sampled from a Gaussian distribution centered around the optimal classifier in the ex-ante distribution $P$. We collect $n=250$ data points from the ex-ante distribution and each one of the ex-post distributions and then estimate $M$ using Algorithm 1 where the minimization step over the set of all matrices is done using the Cholesky decomposition $M=L L^{\top}$ by optimizing for $L$ over the set of lower triangular matrices. After an estimate $\widehat{M}$ is obtained, we plug it in the response map to get $\widehat{T}_{\theta}(x)=X-\widehat{M}^{-1} \beta$. The (estimated) response map $\widehat{T}_{\theta}(x)$ is then used to learn the best performative logistic classifier by minimizing an estimate for the (unnormalized) performative cross-entropy loss

$$
\mathcal{L}(\theta)=-\sum_{k=0}^{K-1} \sum_{i=0}^{n-1}\left\{Y_{i k} \log \left(p_{i k}\right)+\left(1-Y_{i k}\right) \log \left(1-p_{i k}\right)\right\}-\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}\left\{Y_{i} \log \left(p_{i}\right)+\left(1-Y_{i}\right) \log \left(1-p_{i}\right)\right\}
$$

The term $p_{i k}=\left\{1+\exp \left[-\left(\alpha+\beta^{\top} \widehat{T}_{\theta}\left(\widehat{X}_{i k}\right)\right)\right]\right\}^{-1}$ with $\widehat{X}_{i k}=\widehat{T}_{\theta_{k}}^{-1}\left(X_{i k}^{\prime}\right), X_{i k}^{\prime}=T_{\theta_{k}}\left(X_{i k}\right)$ accounts for samples from the ex-post (with $k$ indexing inducement by $\theta_{k}$ ) distributions and the term $p_{i}=\left\{1+\exp \left[-\left(\alpha+\beta^{\top} \widehat{T}_{\theta}\left(X_{i}\right)\right)\right]\right\}$ accounts for samples from the ex-ante distribution.

abstract:
Often in prediction tasks, the predictive model itself can influence the
distribution of the target variable, a phenomenon termed performative
prediction. Generally, this influence stems from strategic actions taken by
stakeholders with a vested interest in predictive models. A key challenge that
hinders the widespread adaptation of performative prediction in machine
learning is that practitioners are generally unaware of the social impacts of
their predictions. To address this gap, we propose a methodology for learning
the distribution map that encapsulates the long-term impacts of predictive
models on the population. Specifically, we model agents' responses as a
cost-adjusted utility maximization problem and propose estimates for said cost.
Our approach leverages optimal transport to align pre-model exposure (ex ante)
and post-model exposure (ex post) distributions. We provide a rate of
convergence for this proposed estimate and assess its quality through empirical
demonstrations on a credit-scoring dataset.
